The Terry Schiavo case played a significant role in end-of-life issues by highlighting the legal, ethical, and medical complexities surrounding the right to die and life-sustaining treatment. It brought national attention to the importance of advance directives and living wills, as it involved prolonged legal battles over the removal of life support for a patient in a persistent vegetative state. The case underscored the need for clear communication and documentation of individuals' wishes regarding end-of-life care.